  "email": "Subject: iOS + wearable anomaly detection — UCSD grad, prototype built on the DETECT approach\n\nDear Dr. Quer,\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior completing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics–Computer Science this September, and I'd like to ask about research software roles in your group.\n\nI build iOS software and have shipped two apps to the App Store — one an ARKit navigation aid for blind users that fuses camera, LiDAR and IMU data entirely on-device. Reading your work on wearable detection of infection and on alert timing, I built a prototype: a SwiftUI app that pulls resting HR, HRV and sleep from HealthKit, learns a personal baseline, and flags deviations with change-point detection. I characterized detection latency against false-positive rate, since an alert that fires too often is worse than none. Code and writeup: [GitHub link].\n\nI'm looking for full-time research software work starting this fall, and the Digital Trials Center is where I'd most like to do it — it's the rare group where both halves of my degree are useful. 20 minutes?\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
