  "track": "Assistive",
  "does": "Human-robot interaction, health informatics and assistive technology, developed through participatory, community-based research 'in close collaboration with disabled people, healthcare workers and community members.' Applications in neurorehabilitation, dementia caregiving and emergency medicine. Very active — HRI 2026 papers already out.",
  "why": "You've done the thing this lab values most and that almost no applicant can claim: built assistive technology that actual blind users tested. Their emphasis on co-design with disabled people means your field trials count as methodology, not just validation.",
  "project": "A participatory-design write-up of HAVEN centered on the users rather than the hardware: what the blind and low-vision testers told you, what you changed in the haptic mapping because of it, and what the system still gets wrong. Add a short critical section on the social model of disability — this lab publishes on reframing assistive robotics that way, and showing you've read it separates you instantly.",
  "email": "Subject: Assistive navigation tech tested with blind users — UCSD senior interested in the lab\n\nDear Dr. Riek,\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior finishing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics–Computer Science this September. I led a four-person team that built and shipped HAVEN, a head-mounted iOS navigation aid for visually impaired users — ARKit/RealityKit SLAM, sub-second obstacle replanning, and five-tactor haptic guidance, all processed on-device.\n\nThe part I most want to talk about isn't the hardware. We tested with blind and low-vision users and changed the haptic mapping substantially because of what they told us, and reading your work on participatory design and on reframing assistive robotics through the social model of disability made me realize how much we did informally that your lab does rigorously. Write-up: [link].\n\nI'm enrolled through September and could start part-time now, full-time after. Would you have 20 minutes?\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
