  "pi": "Tania Morimoto, Assoc. Professor",
  "url": "https://morimotolab.eng.ucsd.edu",
  "score": 80,
  "track": "Haptics",
  "does": "Design and control of flexible and soft robots for unstructured environments, surgical robotics, haptics, mechatronics, and human-in-the-loop control interfaces. Built Hapkit, a low-cost educational haptic device. NSF CAREER and Beckman Young Investigator awards — well funded.",
  "why": "This is the haptics home in San Diego. Your DRV2605L tactor array driven over I2C through a TCA9548A multiplexer, with weighted intensity mapping for direction, is exactly this lab's vocabulary — and you built the whole hardware/firmware/app chain yourself.",
  "project": "Open-source the HAVEN haptic subsystem as a reusable module: Arduino/embedded firmware driving a multiplexed DRV2605L array, a documented command protocol, a host-side Python or Swift library, and a small calibration study measuring direction-identification accuracy across users. Include the thermal data you already have (tactor heating below the IEC skin-contact threshold) — safety characterization is the kind of rigor a medical-robotics lab notices.",
  "email": "Subject: Five-tactor haptic guidance array — UCSD senior, hardware + firmware + app\n\nDear Dr. Morimoto,\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior finishing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics–Computer Science this September. For my senior design project I built the haptics for HAVEN, a head-mounted navigation aid for blind users: five DRV2605L drivers on a TCA9548A I2C multiplexer driven by an Arduino Uno R4, receiving heading corrections over Bluetooth from an ARKit iPhone and translating them into weighted directional vibration, with distinct patterns for doors and no-valid-path states.\n\nI've open-sourced the haptic subsystem as a reusable module with a documented protocol, host library, and a small calibration study of direction-identification accuracy — plus thermal characterization showing tactor heating stayed below the IEC skin-contact threshold: [GitHub link].\n\nI'd value 20 minutes to hear about the lab's current directions. I'm enrolled through September and available part-time now.\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
