  "project": "Reproducibility tooling: take a published computational paper with available data, containerize the full analysis, wrap it in a workflow engine, and publish a one-command reproduction. Document exactly what was broken or undocumented in the original and how you fixed it. Add resource profiling. This is unglamorous and enormously valued by research computing groups.",
  "email": "Subject: Research software / infrastructure — UCSD BioE/Math-CS grad\n\nDear [Hiring Manager],\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior finishing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics–Computer Science this September, writing about research software engineering and infrastructure roles at SDSC.\n\nI build and operate systems, not just scripts. I run a self-hosted Linux service stack — containerized services behind Nginx Proxy Manager with automated TLS, an identity-aware browser-based remote access gateway, and zero-trust tunneling so nothing is exposed directly to the internet. I've shipped two iOS applications to the App Store with automated CI/CD producing signed release binaries.\n\nOn the science side I've taken Bioinformatic Algorithms, Numerical Analysis and Machine Learning, and trained 535 transformer-based models for a course project — which taught me more about storage, throughput and job orchestration than about ML. To demonstrate the overlap I containerized and workflow-wrapped a published analysis into a one-command reproduction: [GitHub link].\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
