  "project": "Package your BENG 202 aptamer tool properly: installable CLI, known-answer test suite, GitHub Actions CI, Docker container, and a Nextflow or Snakemake wrapper so it reproduces end-to-end on another machine. Benchmark runtime and memory against transcriptome size. Workflow engines are the highest-leverage missing keyword on your resume for any core facility.",
  "email": "Subject: Bioinformatics core — UCSD BioE/Math-CS grad, software engineering background\n\nDear [Core Director],\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior finishing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics–Computer Science this September, writing about staff bioinformatics positions in the core.\n\nMy background is a software engineer's rather than a biologist's, which I think is useful in a core. I've shipped two applications to the App Store and maintain CI/CD pipelines producing signed release builds. I've applied that discipline to biology: I took Bioinformatic Algorithms and Biological Databases (implementing local alignment from scratch with a proper CLI) and built a tool that scans the E. coli transcriptome for candidate fluorophore-binding RNA aptamers, scoring k-mers on combined sequence and secondary-structure similarity. I've since packaged it as an installable CLI with unit tests, CI, a Docker container and a Nextflow workflow: [GitHub link].\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
