  "email": "Subject: Low-power BLE sensor telemetry, firmware + iOS — UCSD senior\n\nDear Dr. Mercier,\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior finishing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics–Computer Science this September, writing about research positions in the Center for Wearable Sensors.\n\nI work on both halves of the wearable problem. I wrote multi-threaded ESP32 firmware in C++/FreeRTOS handling concurrent BLE advertising and real-time control tasks, designed the GATT command protocol, and built the companion iOS app in Swift — shipped to the App Store. I also built a head-mounted navigation aid that streams sensor-derived guidance over Core Bluetooth to a haptic array, with roughly six hours of continuous runtime on battery.\n\nI've packaged a demonstration stack — firmware with buffering and reconnect handling, a SwiftUI logging app, and measured power draw across sampling configurations: [GitHub link].\n\nWould you have 20 minutes?\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
