  "project": "Build a methylation-classification pipeline on a public dataset — dimensionality reduction, classifier, and honest evaluation including calibration and behavior on classes with few samples. The rare-class problem is the real one in tumor classification, and you already know that story from your Congress project's 0.91/0.64 recall gap.",
  "email": "Subject: Methylation classification + ML engineering — UCSD BioE/Math-CS grad\n\nDear Dr. Chavez,\n\nI'm a UC San Diego senior finishing B.S. degrees in Bioengineering: Biotechnology and Mathematics-Computer Science this September, writing about computational positions in your lab.\n\nI built a classification pipeline on public methylation data and focused the evaluation on the part that seems hardest in practice — calibration and performance on classes with few training samples: [GitHub link]. I ran into the same problem on a course project where I trained 535 transformer-based classifiers and found a 0.91 vs 0.64 recall gap driven by class imbalance, which taught me to distrust headline accuracy.\n\nI'm also a working software engineer — two App Store releases, CI/CD, containerized infrastructure.\n\nWould you have 20 minutes?\n\nBest regards,\nSuraj Laddagiri\nportfolio.sladdagiri.org",
